WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African-American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Today is Monday, September 12, 2011. My name is Joe Mosnier of the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:33.000
I am with videographer John Bishop. We are in Prospect, Pennsylvania today to complete an interview.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:41.000
The Smithsonian National Museum of African-American History and Culture's Civil Rights History Project.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.000
The project is of course co-sponsored by the Library of Congress.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:55.000
We are sorting out all the information we have.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:01.000
We are delighted today to be with Dr. Thomas Walter Gaither and thank you for the one welcome professor.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:07.000
I want to mention that we have a lovely tour of your heart.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:17.000
I am very glad to be here today.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:23.000
I am very glad to be here today to complete an interview.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:33.000
My parents were Walter B. Gaither and Fannie M. Little Gator.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:41.000
Great Falls was my father's home. My mother Fannie Mae was originally from Anderson, South Carolina.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:51.000
And my mom and dad met while they were students at Friendship Junior College in Rock Hill, South Carolina.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:02:03.000
After they both graduated from Friendship, they of course moved permanently to Great Falls.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:09.000
Initially they were both schoolteachers.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:17.000
You could be a schoolteacher at that time with just a junior college education.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:35.000
My dad did not stay in teaching because he discovered that what was listed on his contract as his per month payment for teaching was not the same as he was receiving.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:43.000
And this was at a time when the boards of education were all composed of white men.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:57.000
And so at the end of the year my father approached the person who was scientist voucher for payment and said I noticed that there is a discrepancy here.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:05.000
It is the five dollar difference between what he was supposed to be paid and what he was receiving.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:17.000
And for questioning the five dollar differential which the school board member was pocketing, my father was terminated as a teacher.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:27.000
My mother continued to be a teacher and in fact my first seven years of formal education was in a one room school.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:33.000
In that area of South Carolina we were actually owned by churches.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:41.000
The state paid the salary of the teacher but various churches across the community had a school.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:47.000
So my and happened to be Pleasant Grove school.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:53.000
Pleasant Grove was a nearby AME Zion church.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:05.000
So for the first seven years of my education that's where I learned to count, to read, to write and all of those kinds of things.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:19.000
The good thing about the one room school was that if you were in third grade you could hear the lessons for the fourth grade, the fifth grade, sixth, so on up the line.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:31.000
So you were on stage at some point but otherwise you were reviewing all the time if you wanted to be reviewing all the time.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:42.000
We had to take to the school a jar that we took a piece of adhesive tape and we put our name on that adhesive tape on the jar.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:48.000
And we turned it upside down by the cooler which was present at the back of the room.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
We of course had no fountains or anything of that sort.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:05:01.000
But right in the middle of the room we had this very large diameter drum that was the heater.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:07.000
And it was never possible to have heat in that room that was even.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:19.000
You would think that it's going to work today and then all of a sudden the lid to the heater would start floating up and down and the whole place would be smoked up.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.000
And then we would have to open the windows.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:26.000
And that was a little bit of a sample of the environment.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:28.000
We didn't have a library.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:34.000
There was a dictionary but I think the dictionary was owned by my mother as the teacher.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:45.000
We didn't know very many of the white kids in the community except by looking in the textbooks that were passed on to us.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:57.000
We could see the kids, the white kids would have used the books and rather than throw them away I would say they would send them or they would they would ship them to us.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:08.000
My mother remained in teaching until the consolidation of schools and that would have been in the early 1950s.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:11.000
Supreme Court decision was 1954.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:14.000
But before that it was some movement in teaching.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:26.000
In fact it was rather amazing that as soon as the south found out that there might be this law banning discrimination or segregation in schools.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:33.000
Suddenly the schools went up and that sort of interesting because we were supposed to be separate but equal all the time.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:37.000
But all of a sudden there's a new black elementary school here.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:39.000
There's one there. There's one there.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:47.000
Now it turns out that I lived right on the edge of two counties, Fairfield County and Chester County.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:55.000
The nearest school in Fairfield County was about 17 miles away at Winnsboro.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:01.000
But the school in Chester County was just about two and a half miles away.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:16.000
So actually I went to elementary school in, I'm sorry I went to high school in Chester County after the seven years in the one room school where my mother was the teacher.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:21.000
The center of the community for my parents was a church.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:24.000
We went to church every Sunday.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:31.000
We went to Sunday school when there were special days we participated in the programs.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:40.000
In fact the first time I remember speaking before an audience of anyone other than my parents would have been at Children's Day at the local church.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:45.000
Pleasant Grove, AME, Zion Church.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:51.000
The district that my church was in was the Columbia Camden District.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:59.000
And ministers served a variable period of time as the pastors of churches.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:06.000
And there was a time very early in my life when we had preaching only on alternate Sundays.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:15.000
But at some point when there was a little bit more capital flowing it got to the point that we had church every Sunday.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:18.000
You mentioned your father loved teaching how to do in that happen.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.000
There was forced out of teaching that.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:24.000
How would I have been then?

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.000
I must have been 11 or 12 someplace.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:32.000
Was the cause of this termination explained to you at the time as a child of that age?

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:35.000
No, no. I learned that later.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:41.000
It was the trusty boards were all white men.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:46.000
But there was usually a figurehead trusty board of black men.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:50.000
And these black men were chosen by the white men.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:55.000
And they were usually people who would not ask questions, who would not rock the boat.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:09:00.000
So that's the way the boards were structured.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:09.000
So after losing his job as a teacher my father went to work at a cotton mill.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:21.000
Since he had a junior college education rather than taking the jobs that are getting the jobs that were traditional for black men of that day.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:25.000
Now this was before the era of power lawn mowers.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:29.000
So there was a yard crew that was all black.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:39.000
And blacks also worked in some of the rooms where the cotton was rendered into cloth that were particularly dirty.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:45.000
The ones where you'd get byssinosis from being cotton fibers and that sort of thing.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:50.000
My dad worked as a fireman, another dirty job.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.000
But the fireman had two responsibilities.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:10:01.000
It was to keep the steam in the boiler plant up to a particular point where all the machines would operate.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:05.000
But you would do that by putting the coal in the furnace.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:12.000
And while that was heating up you'd have some ideas how much to put in because of the experience of having done the job before.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:19.000
They had to go around the mill and stick a key and a little box and turn the key so they were night watchmen.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:23.000
So they did those kind of two jobs together.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:28.000
Well at some point my father lost that job too.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:45.000
I suspect although I'm not sure that it was because of his progressive posture on most things including equal rights, the right to vote, the right to get a decent education, so forth and so on.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:11:02.000
So in early 1950 my father decided to go back to college with five kids and with only jobs that he could do, I shouldn't say this about him.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:20.000
My father was capable of doing a variety of chores. He could wire, he could do brick work, he could do carpentry, he could do all of these things and he would get jobs from people in the community.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:27.000
He was doing these kinds of jobs, handyman, but beyond handyman if he had to.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:33.000
He went back to college at Benedict College in Columbia, South Carolina.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:45.000
And he completed the other two years of his college degree graduating with a Bachelor of Science degree in sociology.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:12:04.000
Well in getting this degree he had been told by a local white businessman who was on the board of trustees at the college that he might have a chance at becoming the principal of the local black high school.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:20.000
Well that was just one member of the board. As it turned out later on there was one local Baptist minister who considered himself to be the sort of highest echelon black in the community.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:27.000
This man did not have a baccalaureate degree, he was simply a minister who had been called by God.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:38.000
He opposed my father getting the job as the principal of the school. By the way it was one of the best things that had happened to my dad because there was a lot of jealousy in the community.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:56.000
And he would not have been able to be an effective principal because he would not have gotten any support from the white community and many of the black people would have also been very jealous of the fact that he had suddenly been able to propel himself into a place of authority and respect.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:20.000
That they could not hope that they would be able to. So he just quit being a person who was working and paying his way through school. In fact he used to come home in the evening from school and he would say let's get organized.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:35.000
And let's get organized meant that we all got in the car. Now we use the car as one would use a truck much to my mother's chagrin. But my father was too poor to buy a truck.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:56.000
So I remember one of the earliest cars was a 1939 Buick. And he would load that 39 Buick with bricks and blocks and mortar and so forth so he could go do the job so he could take care of his family and he could also find some money to pay the tuition to go to school.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:14.000
So at some point we were getting close to finishing high school and there was never any question that we were going to go to college. The question was where and how are we going to pay for going to college.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:37.000
So my dad took one of the gifts that he had in the construction trades industry which was brick masonry and he became a brick mason. And as a brick mason he would travel to jobs all over that area region of South Carolina in the Charlotte Columbia Orangeburg.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:55.000
So in any place you could drive to well I'm going to say in any place you could drive to in a day. Actually I remember once we worked down at the Parris Island Marine Base in Beaufort, South Carolina. And in that case we had to go and stay for five days and then come back home.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:15:16.000
But being a brick mason brick mason's earned a very nice wage and that's what enabled us to find the money to go to school. The problem however was that brick masonry was reliable only when the weather was good.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:37.000
The weather was not good you couldn't lay bricks. And in the South that meant that there were at least two or three months there when it was too cold. But as things would have it favoring my dad and my family he got to the point of being in a typical instance among the mason's employed on a particular job.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:57.000
He got to be sort of the master mason. So when all of the other masons had been dispatched from the job because the job was complete. My dad was the person who stayed around to put up a wall where they needed to so he would very often work through the entire winter.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:12.000
And they had one laborer who worked with him and that is how we were able to get the funds to go to school. Now it turns out that I was the valedictorian of my class and my brother was the salutatorian of the class.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:20.000
And we jointly decided that we would go to Claflin College now Claflin College University in Orangeburg, South Carolina.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:32.000
My scholarship was $75 per year. My brother's scholarship as salutatorian of the class was $50 per year. So that's what got us started in education.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:47.000
But education was always emphasized in my home. Even though we were too poor to have a library, anything that we could find we would read it and we would try to discuss it and try to grow from it.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:17:06.000
So all of our this is going on. My mother was essentially taking care of the family. She was very strong in her insistence that we not get involved in things that took us off the path to going to college and to getting an education.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:10.000
That's a time for all of these.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:15.000
Ah yes, my life is going to be a normal point of scope.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:26.000
Okay, we're back after a short break. But Claflin College, you were talking about your move towards Claflin College but I want to ask a couple of things about your family from that.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:42.000
Sure. Obviously your father and your father, your family had these direct and not so uncommon experiences obviously in terms of suffering for the slightest gesture of self assertion.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:58.000
When conversations about race and race relations have been open in the household, are those things around the dinner table, do you say the brown decision or still are those kinds of things that would have been engaged, conversations by the end of the day?

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:11.000
Those were discussed around the dinner table and my parents shared liberally with what their thoughts were on these kinds of things.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:22.000
I especially remember the till case utterings by my dad and the absolute shame and horror of what had happened to this young man.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:34.000
In fact, I think it was conversations about till that, large in my psyche as one of the motivating factors for participating in the movement later on.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:41.000
Till would have been 1955, that's about the same time as the Montgomery bus boycott.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:50.000
So there were these cumulative things happening out there that were being internalized.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:19:04.000
Among the other things that my dad was a part of, periodically at the cotton mills, there would be an effort to organize the workers, which meant that a union organizer would come in.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:09.000
And my dad was always the person who hosted the union organizer.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:15.000
So that was one of the other factors that would have caused him to lose his job.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:22.000
The union organizers often tried to keep a secret of where they stayed.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:32.000
But of course somebody would know and somebody would go and tell a big boss man, and that would be to your detriment if you happen to be the person.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:38.000
My parents were also openly supportive of the NAACP.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:50.000
I remember when I was quite a youngster, less than 10 years old, we used to go to meetings of the state conference of the NAACP.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:59.000
When my dad would stand as we were going into the auditorium, and there'd often be a whole bunch of adults in the lobby.

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:07.000
And he would hold me up for a while so I could get some air and put me down and then take my brother and hold him up.

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:10.000
But we were very supportive of the NAACP.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:20.000
Now it was also a negative if you were known to be an NAACP member and supportive of the NAACP.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:25.000
But despite that fact, my dad was still a supporter and my mom.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:37.000
I remember that at some point there was a suit by the South Carolina Conference of the NAACP to equalize teacher salaries.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:46.000
And speaking of his family dynamic, my mom and dad were both in favor of the NAACP suit to equalize teaching salaries.

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:56.000
But I had two aunts who were also teachers who were not. They thought the NAACP was stirring up something that was best left alone.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:03.000
And so I remember the sort of tug of war arguments that went on between them.

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:11.000
And at that time, teacher salaries in South Carolina for blacks were very, very poor. And you had to take the National Teacher Examinations.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:20.000
So if you took the National Teacher Examinations and you earned an A in addition to your base salary, you'd get a particular monthly supplement, a B C.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:26.000
Well, all of these school districts with a tax base would high off all the A people and the B people.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:37.000
So it would mean that a little town like Great Falls had bested, good hope for, would be to get the C people, which meant that our teachers were not the best.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:44.000
But they did their best by us with what they had been able to amass and accumulate as knowledge.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:47.000
I don't know if that's your kind of response.

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:49.000
Well, I'll see you very much.

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:50.000
Okay.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:53.000
When your parents in the register vote or not.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:59.000
My parents were registered voters to register to vote.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:10.000
And I should have the form that I feel that I received when I became a qualified elector, a voter in South Carolina.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:14.000
It'd be 18 years old, but I remember registering to vote.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:18.000
Yeah, my parents registered to vote.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:22.000
And they typically voted in elections.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:35.000
I was so involved in making sure that I voted until the first time I was eligible to vote after registering.

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:43.000
I remember a 300-mile trip, 150 miles one way to vote, 150 miles back.

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:51.000
And I have tried to point that out to my students that we shouldn't be casual about our input into the political process.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:54.000
I vote almost every election.

00:22:54.000 --> 00:23:02.000
Even when I've been on leave, I find how long you have to be in the state in order to vote.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:03.000
And register.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:07.000
I remember voting in California a couple of times when I was on sabbatical leave.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:10.000
Yes, both of my parents were qualified electors.

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:18.000
The little thing I was talking about that you have to present saying that you are a qualified elector.

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:25.000
You had to read a section of the South Carolina Constitution and interpret it to the satisfaction of the registrar.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:33.000
But on there is that I do hereby swear that I am not a pauper supported at public expense.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:37.000
I have not been convicted of any of the following crimes.

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:47.000
Stealing chickens, wife beating, you know, all the kinds of things that poor black people might have been involved in.

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:51.000
Public drunkenness and all of those kinds of things.

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:54.000
And that's on the certificate that I have.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:55.000
It probably is not the case.

00:23:55.000 --> 00:23:57.000
At least I hope it's not the case now.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:02.000
And that Winsboro and Fairfield County has moved beyond that.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:15.000
But there were all the disqualifiers, which is somewhat interesting because we've had this recent resurgence of requiring voter ID cards and all of that kind of thing paying poll tax.

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:17.000
Which is a throwback to the same thing.

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:27.000
It's a way of disqualifying those whose input into the political process might be at odds with those who control the political process.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:28.000
More accentuated?

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:29.000
Yes.

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:35.000
So the greatest discs we think we've come, we look around, we're in the same place.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:43.000
Tell me about Orange Bird when you arrived in 56 and what you thought would be your course through college?

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:50.000
Well, I expected with the high school background that I had that I would have to work hard.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:59.000
Because I would be competing with some people who had had, even though all the students at Claplin at the time were black.

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:11.000
People who had better backgrounds, the people who had gone, for example, to CA Johnson in Columbia or some of the high schools in the larger communities.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:14.000
That was some of those people at Claplin.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:20.000
I found myself as my accent haven't told you this yet.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:35.000
But since my mother was our early teacher and we did not have daycare, my brother, right next to me, about a year and a half to two years younger.

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:39.000
And I wound up being in the same graduating class.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:41.000
That's how I was the valedictorian.

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:45.000
And he was the salutatorian because we can find anybody to keep him.

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:47.000
So my mother took him to school.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:56.000
It turned out he was very bright and did misabete in terms of handling the academic information that was put before him.

00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:10.000
I remember finding it an adjustment to be at Claplin, but managing to stay above board academically.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:22.000
I graduated from Claplin, indeed, with honors, with a BS degree in general science with a concentration in biology.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:31.000
Tell me about how race entered into your college experience in one program.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:34.000
I know of course that's after one state is there as well.

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:43.000
And the community will become a place that, in large measure, because of your efforts that were in the 60th, 60th, 60th, to come back.

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:45.000
But there was a story before that.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:52.000
Well, the only choice of going to a college at that time would have been a black college.

00:26:52.000 --> 00:27:00.000
The closest to black colleges would have been Allen University in Columbia and Benedict College in Columbia.

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:03.000
Not too far away was Morris College.

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:05.000
Benedict and Morris are Baptist schools.

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:07.000
Allen is an AEME school.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:16.000
And we didn't, based on the reputation of those colleges, gravitate toward them, choose them.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:22.000
Claplin was a choice that I agreed upon and my brother was pleased with.

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:28.000
So we had no choice of colleges on a racial basis.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:34.000
Let me tell you this little story here because it jumps ahead, but it's apropos.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:41.000
I remember visiting my father in the 70s and 80s.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:47.000
And he had this Clemson College logo around.

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:51.000
And I said, what goes with it with Clemson College?

00:27:51.000 --> 00:28:01.000
And he had chosen to root for Clemson College because of an incident that occurred with me when I was a Claplin.

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:12.000
When I was a Claplin my senior year, I sent money to the Educational Testing Service in Princeton, New Jersey to take the Graduate Record Exam.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:27.000
So there were about a dozen black students from South Carolina State and Claplin who were to take the Graduate Record Exam at the University of South Carolina.

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:44.000
Well, we were told to go to an auditorium on campus. When we arrived, we were intercepted by a professor who said, we cannot permit you to take the GRE on the campus of the University of South Carolina.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:47.000
You people will have to go off campus.

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:54.000
And so across the street, I want to say it was Bull Street. I'm not sure that was the name of the street at the time.

00:28:54.000 --> 00:29:03.000
There was a two story building. The second story of the building was just an open room with some chairs.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:10.000
And this is no exaggeration. The temperature in that room must have been 85 or 90 degrees.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:14.000
And that is where we were forced to take the Graduate Record Exam.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:27.000
And exam that determines all of your possibilities for the future. And these were the conditions or the circumstances under which we were required to take the exam.

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:41.000
Well, I told my dad that when I came home to visit him or went home to visit him after that event. And he had stored that away in his mind that he would never root for the University of South Carolina.

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:51.000
But he would root for Clemson. Now at the time, Clemson was not a University. Clemson started out as an agricultural experiment station. It later became a University.

00:29:51.000 --> 00:30:00.000
But it was the school in South Carolina that he could identify with because he refused to identify with the University of South Carolina.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:07.000
You have drawn into college leadership roles.

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:19.000
Yes. I was the president of the youth chapter of the Claflin College chapter of the NAACP.

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:22.000
Starting what you're trying to do.

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:26.000
Let's see. I know it as a junior.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:36.000
That is how I gravitated into the sit-ins because it was the natural position from which one might assume a role in leadership.

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:42.000
Tell me about the first step.

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:57.000
Let me maybe describe the youth chapter of the NAACP in campus Ben and how it connected you to the state NAACP apparatus and how it then led you forward.

00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:12.000
Okay. The first year I was president of the campus chapter, I would say maybe out of 200 students we may have had 25 or 30 people who were members.

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:23.000
I think it was less than 200. It wasn't very large University. If you were a student you would know everyone on campus.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:30.000
You would know which year they were in and you would also know their hometowns and all of that.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:41.000
It was a very small, very closely knit community. Now after the sit-ins started almost everyone on campus joined the NAACP chapter.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:32:02.000
There were a couple of young people or students there who were afraid to join because they thought that word of their joining as youth members of a college chapter of the NAACP might get back to their communities and there would be reprisals against their parents.

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:11.000
I can remember a couple of those people actually coming and apologizing to me that they could not be members of the youth chapter of the NAACP.

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:33.000
Now as a youth chapter NAACP president I was permitted to attend regional meetings of the NAACP. That is where I would have met first people like Ruby Hurley or Amos C. Brown or Medgar Evers.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:54.000
There were people there from South Carolina, Tennessee, Mississippi, not Alabama. Alabama at the time the NAACP was illegal. So we didn't have anybody slipping through who were parts of the Alabama civil rights scene.

00:32:54.000 --> 00:33:07.000
So when the sit-ins started in Greensboro, North Carolina February 1st, 1960 the first sit-ins in South Carolina were at Rock Hill.

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:21.000
And as soon as we heard about that we said the same problems that are being addressed in North Carolina and North of here in Rock Hill are here so we got to organize too.

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:32.000
And that's where we sort of expanded out from this NAACP youth chapter to organizing and participating in the sit-ins.

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:34.000
Yeah, maybe that's it.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:42.000
Tell me about the process that you undertook to bring the campus chapter and the wider campus forward into active.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:50.000
Well it wasn't just the wider Claflin College campus. It was also the South Carolina state students that we would have to engage.

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:57.000
Well first of all we didn't know the first thing about nonviolence, how to organize the sit-in.

00:33:57.000 --> 00:34:13.000
So we were fortunately visited by a someone had sent a man named James T. McCain who was from Sumter, South Carolina and he worked for an organization called the Congress of Rachel E. Quality, a Corps.

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:24.000
And Corps had a little thing that was called CORE Rules for Action. It was also a little booklet called Cracking the Color Line by James Peck.

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:36.000
And so those were the very first kinds of sources that we were privy to to form the philosophical backlog for the organization of the sit-ins.

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:45.000
The Orangeburg sit-ins were actually organized by a group of students from South Carolina state and Claflin College.

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:55.000
And we met in the old JJ C. Brooks auditorium, actually Jim Nazium on the campus of Claflin College.

00:34:55.000 --> 00:35:15.000
So with these pamphlets and so forth and with the inspiration of Dr. King's book Stride Toward Freedom, we started putting together sociodromas of situations that might be faced if we were doing a sitting sit-in or if we were picketing.

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:29.000
So that's sort of how we got going. Now the South Carolina state students to my knowledge did not have a youth chapter of NAACP. But they were right there with us as we organized.

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:39.000
So we actually started sort of a local student movement association with one person from Claflin College that was me and one person from South Carolina state.

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:47.000
Not absolutely certain, but the person from South Carolina state may have been Chuck McDew. Chuck McDew was there very early on.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:36:02.000
So what we did with a little bit more knowledge of what sit-ins were about and what the philosophy was was to train a group of about a dozen or so sort of secondary student leaders.

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:13.000
These would be the people who would be involved in helping to organize and communicate the philosophy and the modus operandi for Claflin College but would also do the same kind for state.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:23.000
Now I think that one of the persons in that group may have been James E. Clyburn, the current House of Representatives person from South Carolina.

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:26.000
So Clyburn was involved very early on.

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:34.000
I think there's probably an important point to be made about the fact that Claflin College is private and safe.

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:52.000
That is, that is, that is, that is, you're absolutely correct because I think there may have even been for activities of a similar nature, some expulsions from South Carolina state.

00:36:52.000 --> 00:37:15.000
Because at the time the persons who were chosen to be the administrators of predominantly black state schools were often chosen because of their ability to suppress student uprisings, whatever their nature, if the nature was in opposition to the existing status of maintaining segregation and so forth and so on.

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:35.000
So at Claflin College we could organize, we had the freedom to do so. There was in the initial groups a disproportionate representation of guys because at the time girls could be out of the dormitories only until seven o'clock or seven thirty.

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:46.000
So we had to communicate what we had done to the girls because they couldn't be there sitting sitting with us.

00:37:46.000 --> 00:38:15.000
As much as you can conjure and recall it from this distance, it must have been a wide range of emotions and a wide range of questions and a wide range of uncertainties that were, that that you would have had at a time trying to launch into something as complex and prospectively difficult as organizing in Orangeburg [South Carolina].

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:35.000
We were idealists. We were in many instances quite enamored with the possibilities for using nonviolence as a strategy for promoting social change.

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:53.000
We were, of course, fearful of our safety. We were fearful of the reprisals that might be levied at our parents. But we also realized that if we didn't move, we were going to stay in the same circumstance.

00:38:53.000 --> 00:39:11.000
That was a motivating factor that the students have moved in North Carolina. They've moved in Rock Hill. We have to move in Orangeburg. So that despite the potential pitfalls was a compelling and a motivating force for us.

00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:35.000
Now I should say that this was done almost exclusively by students. There was no, there was a very good local relationship with the adult NAACP. But we really didn't go to the president of the Orangeburg chapter of the NAACP saying we want to organize sit-ins.

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:58.000
Because the NAACP's approach to this whole problem was fundamentally different from the approach that we were interested in. We were interested in nonviolent direct action. We were not interested in having one stuttered arrested and then having that person be a test case and getting a court ruling that at some point would say, well, you guys can go sit at the lunch counter.

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:21.000
I happen to think that a large part of the strength and reserve of my generation, at least, the passion for our involvement was the active participation and the suffering that we endure. That's very different than if you file a suit and you sit and somebody said, well, you can go sit at the lunch counter tomorrow.

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:40.000
This is that same question I was making, or climate I was making about being compelled to go and vote, or feeling an obligation to go and vote. That's different. And that's, I think, one of the positive attributes, the personal level for those who participated in the sit-ins.

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:51.000
The day in Argeburg, when we had a mass arrest, 350 people arrested, 50th March, yes.

00:40:51.000 --> 00:41:06.000
City jail filled, County jail filled, open air stockade. The president of the Claflin chapter of the NAACP was in Columbia and we had not even told him.

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:21.000
Not that I think he would have been objected, one I owed him. But this was our movement, this was our time to move and we didn't want any tempering from anybody about, well, don't do this, wait till tomorrow to do this, that kind of thing.

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:50.000
We felt that our elders had had an opportunity, they had sat on it, we were not going to be similarly situated. So we reasoned that if we move, there's no choice. I mean, you got 350 piece loving young people who have behaved in a nonviolent manner, they have been arrested. What are the elders going to do? There's nothing, they'd be forced to be supported of us. And that was the way we reasoned it.

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:55.000
I should have filmed it that day.

00:41:55.000 --> 00:42:08.000
Well, it was an interesting day to say the least by the way, I was not arrested on that day for sitting in.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:17.480
Eventually, they had students in the county courthouse where they were,

00:42:17.480 --> 00:42:24.480
or they were already citing, booking them, I'm sure, because there was so many people that they had to deal with.

00:42:24.480 --> 00:42:34.480
And I was standing outside talking to Herbert Wright, the National NAACP Youth Secretary.

00:42:34.480 --> 00:42:51.480
And the policeman came over and said, you have to move. You can't stand here and talk. And I said, well, I started walking around. The courthouse is in a square, and the sidewalk is around the perimeter.

00:42:51.480 --> 00:43:04.480
Well, after I went around one time, they took me out and arrested me anyway. And I was also charged with breaching the piece and disturbing the piece.

00:43:05.480 --> 00:43:21.480
At the end of that day, just an enormous number of people arrested and involved, I remembered that we met back up at the gymnasium on the campus of Claflin College.

00:43:21.480 --> 00:43:29.480
And that was the first time that I remember meeting Matthew J. Perry Jr, who just died recently.

00:43:29.480 --> 00:43:44.480
I remember how gracious he was in telling us that we would be defended. The NAACP would use its resources for our defense.

00:43:44.480 --> 00:43:51.480
In fact, he was so gracious. And so I think, well, maybe we've won something here. It was just the tone of his voice.

00:43:51.480 --> 00:44:02.480
But we felt good to have contributed that one little skirmish in an enormous size battle for equal rights.

00:44:02.480 --> 00:44:08.480
It's simply the right to sit at a lunch counter and eat a hamburger and dignity like any other American.

00:44:08.480 --> 00:44:21.480
Let me ask you about a couple things in the run up to that day. When you first encountered the philosophy of nonviolent direct action, it seems that it resonated with you, I take.

00:44:21.480 --> 00:44:30.480
And I'm curious about it. Can you talk about that a little bit? If that did or did not, in important ways, connect to your personal faith through the church and the Christian and those things.

00:44:30.480 --> 00:44:47.480
It ultimately did, but it did not initially. The first time I heard someone talk about nonviolence was man by the name of Glenn Smiley, who worked for the Fellowship of Reconciliation.

00:44:47.480 --> 00:44:59.480
He gave a lecture at Claflin talking about nonviolence. And I remember standing up and saying, that is what is wrong with black people.

00:44:59.480 --> 00:45:15.480
We have been two, we've been nonviolent too long. But that was my naivete sitting and accepting something that is demeaning or demoralizing is not nonviolence.

00:45:15.480 --> 00:45:30.480
But that shows you where I was in terms of my comprehension of nonviolence. So I actually started to embrace the philosophy when I started to learn something about its tactics and techniques from this man James T. McCain.

00:45:30.480 --> 00:45:35.480
Yeah, that was my next question. I want to have you describe James McHenry.

00:45:35.480 --> 00:45:47.480
One of the most important people in the civil rights struggle for South Carolina especially, because that was his home state.

00:45:47.480 --> 00:45:58.480
Very low key man, a person whose primary commitment was to the cause, not to any kind of personal advancement that it would bring him.

00:45:58.480 --> 00:46:15.480
He was tactically a nonviolent person. If you wanted to go into the real substance and philosophy of nonviolence, you'd have to read home of Jack's autobiography or Louis Fischer's Gandhi or something of that sort.

00:46:15.480 --> 00:46:38.480
Which I later read and which I found to be remarkably instructive about how Gandhi connected his, how Gandhi staged his battle against the British for Indian independence using nonviolence.

00:46:38.480 --> 00:46:47.480
Tell me more about the thing.

00:46:47.480 --> 00:47:02.480
Well, I would consider James T. McCain to have been my mentor in the civil rights movement. He was interested in me as a person and also as one who would be a participant in the movement.

00:47:02.480 --> 00:47:18.480
And in fact, he was the person who persuaded me to attend a session held by CORE. This would have been in the summer, I believe, of 1960.

00:47:18.480 --> 00:47:43.480
CORE held at Miami, what was called an (CORE) Action Institute. And at this (CORE) Action Institute, all of the upper echelon of CORE and a large number of students from the New Orleans area especially, we were there to learn about how to stage sit-ins and so forth.

00:47:43.480 --> 00:47:55.480
In fact, that was the second time I was arrested because I was sitting at a table in a little community that is called Hollywood, California.

00:47:55.480 --> 00:48:03.480
Hollywood, yeah, Hollywood, Florida, yes, you're exactly right. Hollywood, Florida, with a girl from New York named Dottie Miller.

00:48:03.480 --> 00:48:14.480
Doddy later was for a short time married to Bob Zellner. Bob Zellner may be the person who is better known in terms of participation in the civil rights.

00:48:14.480 --> 00:48:21.480
We play this game where you say I'm thinking of somebody and you have a whole bunch of clues and you finally say who the person is.

00:48:21.480 --> 00:48:35.480
And the management of this restaurant decided that they didn't want us in their restaurant. So we were arrested, Dottie Miller and this whole group.

00:48:35.480 --> 00:48:51.480
And we spent 10 or 12 days in the date, county jail. Bernard Lafayette was among the other persons that one would identify with who were parts of this group.

00:48:51.480 --> 00:49:02.480
And we had the most interesting charge I've ever heard. The charge was ejection of undesirable guests.

00:49:02.480 --> 00:49:12.480
Ejection of undesirable guests. When it came before the judge, the judge said no adjudication.

00:49:12.480 --> 00:49:22.480
But if you guys stay down here and if you are involved in similar activities, I reserve the right, I'll put you on probation.

00:49:22.480 --> 00:49:28.480
And if you're on probation, then you could wind up back in jail again.

00:49:28.480 --> 00:49:41.480
I don't understand either. That was the charge. Ejection of undesirable guests. It wasn't trespassing. It wasn't reaching the piece. That was the charge.

00:49:41.480 --> 00:49:48.480
You mentioned that this is a Miami and I think that Miami meeting, if my date arrived was August 1960.

00:49:48.480 --> 00:49:56.480
So you would have graduated from MA. Were you already on staff as a field secretary or have that not happened yet?

00:49:56.480 --> 00:50:08.480
No, that had not happened yet. Right after I graduated, I worked in South Carolina with a man named Frank Robinson,

00:50:08.480 --> 00:50:15.480
who was associated with CORE, Frank Robinson, who was from Sumter, South Carolina and Jim McKain.

00:50:15.480 --> 00:50:23.480
I was working with a group of about four or five people and we were doing voter registration in South Carolina.

00:50:23.480 --> 00:50:34.480
So we would go to churches in the evenings and we talk about the importance of registering and voting and that kind of thing.

00:50:34.480 --> 00:50:42.480
Yeah, I went from there to the (CORE) Action Institute and then I was hired on by CORE.

00:50:42.480 --> 00:50:49.480
I'm going to bring in some more threads here. There are many threads, so I'll have to bring in another thing.

00:50:49.480 --> 00:50:53.480
There are so many things here. I'm a non-violence question again.

00:50:53.480 --> 00:50:58.480
So initially you told that very interesting story about your first unhearingness was skepticism.

00:50:58.480 --> 00:51:15.480
I think in contact maybe. Did you see its merits first in tactical terms or did you go all that distance to sort of internalizing it and being committed to it as a more encompassing force?

00:51:15.480 --> 00:51:27.480
No, I went to it in tactical terms. I think it takes a lot of discipline study to go to nonviolence in the philosophical sense of Gandhi.

00:51:27.480 --> 00:51:38.480
In fact, there were times and this is jumping forward. There were times when we were on the road gang in Rock Hill.

00:51:38.480 --> 00:51:50.480
When as the adult sort of in that group, my mind was clicking in, how would Gandhi behave in this situation?

00:51:51.480 --> 00:52:02.480
And we often discussed the difference between tactical nonviolence and nonviolence as a more involved personal philosophy of life.

00:52:02.480 --> 00:52:10.480
Well, I knew how I thought Gandhi would have handled the situation. Gandhi would volunteer to clean the toilets.

00:52:10.480 --> 00:52:17.480
And I was not likely to be able to get my young colleagues to say, this is what we should do.

00:52:17.480 --> 00:52:22.480
They're practical limits sometimes. We were loading trucks with sand.

00:52:22.480 --> 00:52:30.480
You can throw only so many shovels in. But I happen to think that Gandhi would probably have thrown shovels until he collapsed.

00:52:31.480 --> 00:52:43.480
And so there was always that sort of editing between the philosophy as a technique and the philosophy as a way of life.

00:52:43.480 --> 00:52:48.480
I think one gradually grows into it, the philosophy as a way of life.

00:52:48.480 --> 00:52:52.480
And I don't think I have met a lot of people who have done that.

00:52:52.480 --> 00:53:13.480
There are some people whose knowledge of nonviolence is far superior to mine, who might respect for their ability to connect all of this together in a life encompassing philosophy rather than as a tactic or technique for acquiring human rights or promoting issues of justice.

00:53:13.480 --> 00:53:21.480
Along the way, say, coming through the spring semester of 1960, and you can hear the early summary, start this for the registration work.

00:53:21.480 --> 00:53:24.480
What's the reaction to your family?

00:53:24.480 --> 00:53:40.480
My family was very supportive, extremely supportive. I kept in contact, but my family was deeply religious, both my mom and my dad.

00:53:40.480 --> 00:53:47.480
If you were asking them about their concerns for me, they would probably say, the Lord will take care of them.

00:53:47.480 --> 00:53:57.480
And I'd just put that in the hands of the Lord. That would have been their response, and that's truly the way they felt.

00:53:57.480 --> 00:54:12.480
So even though they knew I was in danger, somehow they were optimistic that I would return with all of my senses and would not have been permanently impaired in any way.

00:54:12.480 --> 00:54:22.480
I'm not sure that they realized how dangerous it was, but you have to also realize that they were in danger too, in a small community.

00:54:22.480 --> 00:54:37.480
And they were not nonviolent. Let me tell you this story. When we were in jail in Rock Hill, some of the local people who had known my dad forever came to him and said, we will protect you.

00:54:37.480 --> 00:54:51.480
While your son is 29 miles away on the road game. And I'm not sure what my dad told him, but I don't think he encouraged them because there was no one sitting in a car at the fence around my place

00:54:51.480 --> 00:55:04.480
to shoot someone who would come there. But while I was in jail in Rock Hill, a cross was burned on the lawn of my parents' house.

00:55:04.480 --> 00:55:13.480
And I remember when my dad told me that. He said, and if I had seen him, he said it would have been the last cross that he would have burned.

00:55:13.480 --> 00:55:28.480
And it occurred to me that I wouldn't think of shooting someone for burning a cross. That's where I had grown in nonviolence. But my dad was a different generation, a whole different ethic about how you go about protecting your family.

00:55:28.480 --> 00:55:33.480
It's one of the primary things that a man does who has a family.

00:55:33.480 --> 00:55:42.480
Tell me about some of your early ones. I think they will.

00:55:42.480 --> 00:55:51.480
We're back after short break. Let me ask you to talk a little bit about your emerging impressions of this organization called CORE.

00:55:51.480 --> 00:56:01.480
You obviously met Mr. Cain through the spring. He becomes a very mentor. You go into this photo registration effort. Are you getting much of a sense of CORE at the national level?

00:56:01.480 --> 00:56:13.480
How does your sense of that emerge? Yes. I was getting an impression of CORE at the national level because I had occasion to visit the CORE office in New York.

00:56:13.480 --> 00:56:24.480
And at the time, the CORE office with the exception of James T. McCain, most of the staff was white.

00:56:24.480 --> 00:56:38.480
And the executive secretary of CORE, when I first learned about CORE, was very slightly built white man by the name of James R. "Jim" Robinson.

00:56:38.480 --> 00:56:52.480
James R. "Jim" Robinson, a very nice person, very committed to the cause. And CORE had actually since its inception in 1942 at the University of Chicago.

00:56:52.480 --> 00:57:07.480
And primarily a northern organization, composed of liberal people who believe that non-violent direct action could be used to promote social change.

00:57:07.480 --> 00:57:24.480
So once I started going to the CORE national office, I started meeting other people and my impression of the possibilities for non-violent direct action and my respect for the commitment of the people involved was ever increasing.

00:57:24.480 --> 00:57:32.480
I think it's the case that your first trip up to the office was as a consequence of the leadership role you had on the clock?

00:57:32.480 --> 00:57:48.480
Yes, no question about it. Well, it's the first time I'd ever rode on an airplane. I remember going to the airport in Columbia and flying up to New York,

00:57:48.480 --> 00:57:59.480
and the airport in Columbia was either way very small, and there may have been eight or ten gates or so, rather unlikely, the airport that is there now.

00:57:59.480 --> 00:58:17.480
Yeah, and I remember meeting Jimmy McDonald and Gordon Carey and Marvin Rich and so forth and being sort of shown a little bit of the big city, never having been to a city like New York before.

00:58:17.480 --> 00:58:27.480
To that summer in your brother registration work, what are the memories that emerges, or most vividly, for you?

00:58:27.480 --> 00:58:45.480
I remember talking, see what we did, we went individually and talked with people, and often we chose to go to projects where there was a concentration of people, many of whom would have not been registered voters.

00:58:45.480 --> 00:59:00.480
And we would actually try to engage people in conversations about the importance of voting, and it would always get down to this, especially with the little old ladies.

00:59:01.480 --> 00:59:16.480
I will go and register and vote if my preacher says it's okay. It was almost always that the minister had to give his blessings, or you would not want to get them to...

00:59:16.480 --> 00:59:24.480
Now there were some people who would, after you told them why it was important, will say, well, I'll go down and I'll give it a try.

00:59:24.480 --> 00:59:35.480
But I remember almost without fail, the people who were resistant, it was a matter of, if the minister, if my preacher says it's okay, I may go give it a try.

00:59:35.480 --> 00:59:42.480
I'm not sure how many of those people we ever really got to register and vote, but we did have some success.

00:59:42.480 --> 00:59:51.480
And again, we chose projects and places where you could go from one door to the next to the next. And it was almost a one-on-one kind of thing with our team.

00:59:52.480 --> 01:00:12.480
Through that summer in 1960, there's much, much, much active conversation and debate even in the civil rights community, such as it was structured in its pieces and different parts of it in that moment, about how do we forward?

01:00:12.480 --> 01:00:25.480
Because obviously the city in oftentimes were met with most oftentimes, were met with very, very vigorous and ongoing resistance, and yielded relatively little of anything in terms of a direct result.

01:00:25.480 --> 01:00:41.480
So I'm wondering about your thoughts, to that period, because obviously this is going to connect to the emergence of another idea about how to move forward, that you will play a very large part in helping to convocate and advocate.

01:00:41.480 --> 01:01:04.480
Well, the early sit-ins essentially resulted in people sitting at the lunch counters and being arrested, and then posting bond. And the bond was used by the state to perhaps continue the practice.

01:01:04.480 --> 01:01:19.480
And so I felt that there should be more, perhaps, of a commitment on our part, being willing to suffer for something that we really wanted to have happen.

01:01:19.480 --> 01:01:32.480
So that's why a year, almost to the date, after the first sit-ins, we got involved in the jail-no-bail policy with the Friendship 9. That was deliberate.

01:01:32.480 --> 01:01:47.480
And that protest was really to occur one year after the first sit-ins, and it was to take us to a different level of commitment. And that's the essence of the jail-no-bail.

01:01:47.480 --> 01:01:56.480
Now, there were quantities about what had been happening previously in the people who were with the Student Unviolent Coordinating Committee.

01:01:56.480 --> 01:02:15.480
There were doubtlessly some NAACP chapters that had jumped on board and so forth, who were dealing with the same thing. And so jail-no-bail would turn out to be an important commitment level that we had not seen before,

01:02:15.480 --> 01:02:33.480
which we would hope would appeal to people of goodwill. These college students, who were just simply sitting at a lunch counter, they were arrested, and they are in jail now, or they are on a road gang now, there's something wrong with me.

01:02:33.480 --> 01:02:43.480
And I'm talking about if someone were really interested in social justice, or addressing the problems that we have in this country relative to race.

01:02:43.480 --> 01:02:53.480
So without doing anything active, at least the people in the other parts of the country, could say, well, we're not going to patronize that store.

01:02:53.480 --> 01:03:21.480
I'm going to insist in my own personal life that we find a way to treat those young people fairly. So that willingness to suffering, we had hoped that that would appeal to the good-natured sense of social justice that we hoped permeated enough people in the country for some positive change to occur.

01:03:21.480 --> 01:03:33.480
Let me reach back again, because some of these threats that are bringing us forward here. So I think in the spring of 60, in fact, a group of students who are core affiliated at 4 a.m.

01:03:33.480 --> 01:03:34.480
Oh, yeah. Okay.

01:03:34.480 --> 01:03:37.480
And I'm going to say, in the 60 days, who would have known about that?

01:03:37.480 --> 01:03:38.480
Yes, yes.

01:03:38.480 --> 01:03:51.480
That is generally emerging, I mean, generally cited in the literature as sort of a first instance of a kind of jail no bail.

01:03:51.480 --> 01:03:56.480
May I interrupt them, I'm going to hear.

01:03:56.480 --> 01:04:06.480
Sometimes I think the important thing is not perhaps what you do, but the context that you do it in.

01:04:07.480 --> 01:04:20.480
And I would never detract one eye odor from the significance of what happened to this core group in Tallahassee, Patricia Stephens (Due), Priscilla Stephens, and those people.

01:04:20.480 --> 01:04:28.480
But outside of core echelons, I'm not sure how well that particular protest was known.

01:04:28.480 --> 01:04:41.480
But I think we had had hundreds of students arrested in the early 1960s after the sit-in movement started up in Greensboro.

01:04:41.480 --> 01:04:44.480
And we had a context for the Friendship 9.

01:04:44.480 --> 01:04:50.480
And I think it was being in the strategic place at the strategic time.

01:04:50.480 --> 01:05:02.480
And it still merits a significant note historically because there were certainly other groups that could have done the same thing.

01:05:02.480 --> 01:05:07.480
But ours was the group that did the critical thing.

01:05:07.480 --> 01:05:14.480
Absolutely. I'm trying to trace how you go to Miami in August of 1960.

01:05:14.480 --> 01:05:21.480
And earlier in recounting that arrest there, you made it seem, and I want to make sure I'm clear on this.

01:05:21.480 --> 01:05:25.480
The arrest there was intentional or kind of surprised you in that.

01:05:25.480 --> 01:05:28.480
Well, this was an (CORE) Action Institute.

01:05:28.480 --> 01:05:37.480
And in the (CORE) Action Institute, we would very often have, for example, we would have a white and a black sitting at a lunch counter.

01:05:37.480 --> 01:05:46.480
And we would have observers that were white and black, and we were trying to sense the sentiment of the position of the management.

01:05:46.480 --> 01:05:54.480
And so if the white and black who were the test group were served, then the white or the black who were the observers would say,

01:05:54.480 --> 01:05:57.480
well, I'm going to not patronize this place anymore.

01:05:57.480 --> 01:06:01.480
You're letting a black person eat down at the end of the counter.

01:06:01.480 --> 01:06:04.480
So you have no way when you go in to do that.

01:06:04.480 --> 01:06:07.480
You have no way of knowing how the police are going to perceive it.

01:06:07.480 --> 01:06:10.480
They might just come in and arrest both of the groups.

01:06:10.480 --> 01:06:14.480
And so the arrest in Miami was really sort of accidental.

01:06:14.480 --> 01:06:20.480
We were not planning to be arrested, but we realized that we might be arrested.

01:06:20.480 --> 01:06:33.480
And in fact, and some of the proceedings of the (CORE) Action Institute, there were some people whose level of commitment to what we were doing was not quite up to the level of being arrested.

01:06:33.480 --> 01:06:43.480
They wound up being arrested, and they actually were somewhat sore about the fact that they were arrested.

01:06:43.480 --> 01:06:51.480
But you had to realize that if you were in this particular game, that was all a part of the territory.

01:06:51.480 --> 01:06:53.480
You spent time as you mentioned the day County Jail.

01:06:53.480 --> 01:06:54.480
Yes.

01:06:54.480 --> 01:06:56.480
That would have been your first extended stay.

01:06:56.480 --> 01:06:57.480
Yes. Yes.

01:06:57.480 --> 01:07:02.480
Not a nice place to spend time at all.

01:07:02.480 --> 01:07:14.480
We were in a cell block that may have had 35 men or so, including murderers.

01:07:14.480 --> 01:07:31.480
For the most part, the prisoners were very respectful to us, but to anybody else who came in the cell block, there were certain expectations that were enforced by the prisoners.

01:07:31.480 --> 01:07:36.480
The cell block person who was at the top of the hierarchy.

01:07:36.480 --> 01:07:45.480
And by that, I mean the person who was the strongest and who wielded enough power to make other underlings carry out his orders.

01:07:45.480 --> 01:07:51.480
I remember one night, elderly man was put into the cell block.

01:07:51.480 --> 01:08:00.480
And one of the underlings went over to him and said, Pops, you have to take a shower.

01:08:00.480 --> 01:08:05.480
And this man said, well, who the hell do you think you are? I'm not taking a shower.

01:08:05.480 --> 01:08:10.480
I just got arrested for being drunk out on the streets. I'm clean.

01:08:10.480 --> 01:08:17.480
And he said, the underling went back and told the guy who was the sort of head of the cell block.

01:08:17.480 --> 01:08:24.480
And he said, well, either he takes a shower now or I'm going to beat the hell out of you.

01:08:24.480 --> 01:08:29.480
And so this underling goes back and tells the man you got to take a shower.

01:08:29.480 --> 01:08:36.480
And he gave him the same argument before. And within a matter of moments, this guy is being beaten by this underling.

01:08:36.480 --> 01:08:40.480
And he's thrown into the shower and he takes a shower.

01:08:40.480 --> 01:08:45.480
So it was that sort of environment, not an environment at all.

01:08:45.480 --> 01:08:51.480
First time I saw guys make hot chocolate in a cell block.

01:08:51.480 --> 01:08:55.480
And there were these metal cups.

01:08:55.480 --> 01:09:00.480
And they would take a Mars candy bar or Milky Way.

01:09:00.480 --> 01:09:04.480
And they would put it right up next to the incandescent lamp, a light.

01:09:04.480 --> 01:09:08.480
They could find enough to attach it there.

01:09:08.480 --> 01:09:12.480
And the chocolate would melt into the water, stir it around.

01:09:12.480 --> 01:09:17.480
And that was hot chocolate.

01:09:17.480 --> 01:09:21.480
When, when, when, core invites you to become a build secretary, right?

01:09:21.480 --> 01:09:26.480
It kind of on the other side of the Miami experience.

01:09:26.480 --> 01:09:31.480
What was your thought about that opportunity and what you might be doing?

01:09:31.480 --> 01:09:40.480
I was delighted at the opportunity to be able to go and work full time in the, in the movement.

01:09:40.480 --> 01:09:45.480
The background had been in the NAACP of course.

01:09:45.480 --> 01:09:53.480
But I did not agree with the philosophy of the NAACP in terms of how you go about promoting social change.

01:09:53.480 --> 01:09:58.480
But I was pleased that I had the contacts with the NAACP.

01:09:58.480 --> 01:10:06.480
So when I went to Jackson, Mississippi to work, the only person that I really knew in Jackson was Medge Evers.

01:10:06.480 --> 01:10:13.480
And I had met Medge Evers at these regional meetings of the NAACP when I was a student at Klaflon.

01:10:13.480 --> 01:10:18.480
So you actually went immediately to Mississippi in 2016?

01:10:18.480 --> 01:10:23.480
No, no, I had a variety of assignments for core.

01:10:23.480 --> 01:10:26.480
I remember working in Kentucky.

01:10:26.480 --> 01:10:29.480
I remember working in California.

01:10:29.480 --> 01:10:32.480
I remember working in Arizona.

01:10:32.480 --> 01:10:37.480
Wherever there were, people would write core.

01:10:37.480 --> 01:10:48.480
And they would express an interest in addressing a problem of discrimination in their communities where nonviolent direct action could be used.

01:10:48.480 --> 01:10:55.480
And core would then send out a person to train them, to advise them so forth and so on.

01:10:55.480 --> 01:11:00.480
So that's how I got to work in some of these, these other communities.

01:11:00.480 --> 01:11:10.480
No, I got the Jackson assignment because I had been key in coming up with the idea of a freedom ride in the first place.

01:11:10.480 --> 01:11:20.480
And because I had made all of these contacts along the route that made it sort of a natural kind of thing for me to be the scout for the ride.

01:11:20.480 --> 01:11:23.480
It's just amazing to me to go through this conversation.

01:11:23.480 --> 01:11:29.480
I'm so thick in so much of this history that every time I, every, there's just more and more and more.

01:11:29.480 --> 01:11:32.480
So I have to slow you down again.

01:11:32.480 --> 01:11:36.480
But as we certainly will come on the freedom rides here pretty soon.

01:11:36.480 --> 01:11:45.480
But through the fall of 1960, one of the things then that you are very heavily involved with is beginning to do the training with the folks from Raquel.

01:11:45.480 --> 01:11:49.480
And can you describe that because that's going to be built at the January 31.

01:11:49.480 --> 01:11:54.480
The training with the folks from Raquel was done at Claflin College.

01:11:54.480 --> 01:12:03.480
And I think that Gordon Carey was there and James T. McCain may have been in and out of there.

01:12:03.480 --> 01:12:07.480
And the primary emphasis was on the socio-dramas.

01:12:07.480 --> 01:12:18.480
The amazing thing about the friendship, not, was that we took essentially a group of college students who had no

01:12:18.480 --> 01:12:24.480
knowledge at all of tactical nonviolence.

01:12:24.480 --> 01:12:33.480
And we pulled off one of the most important protest events of the movement.

01:12:33.480 --> 01:12:36.480
I mean, I look back at that now.

01:12:36.480 --> 01:12:43.480
Normally to do this kind of thing, if you expect people to be arrested and to spend 30 days on a road gang,

01:12:43.480 --> 01:12:50.480
you go find some guys who studied nonviolence and who have been involved in protests like we did for the freedom rides.

01:12:50.480 --> 01:12:54.480
The first riders were not randomly chosen people.

01:12:54.480 --> 01:12:57.480
They were people. You had to submit an application.

01:12:57.480 --> 01:13:07.480
Everybody had to feel comfortable with everybody else in terms of their ability to behave in a nonviolent way or fashion.

01:13:07.480 --> 01:13:10.480
That's not what we had with the friendship 9.

01:13:10.480 --> 01:13:12.480
We were able to pull it off.

01:13:12.480 --> 01:13:15.480
Great.

01:13:15.480 --> 01:13:18.480
Because those are really a great bunch of guys.

01:13:18.480 --> 01:13:20.480
One question I'm curious about.

01:13:20.480 --> 01:13:23.480
Why January 31 and not February 1?

01:13:23.480 --> 01:13:36.480
Well, the students were interested in being able to register for the next semester of classes.

01:13:36.480 --> 01:13:50.480
And so our choice of the date that wasn't exactly opposite the starting date of February 1, 1960, February 1, 1961, was to accommodate that.

01:13:50.480 --> 01:13:52.480
So the guys could get registered.

01:13:52.480 --> 01:14:03.480
So that if things went well and they spent their 30 days, they might be able to be in enough contact with their teachers to not lose a whole semester of schooling.

01:14:03.480 --> 01:14:10.480
And so that's the reason for that.

01:14:10.480 --> 01:14:23.480
Yeah, so that the so that the friendship college students could register and have the potential for completing a semester,

01:14:23.480 --> 01:14:33.480
even though they were going to be on the road gang in Rock Hill, we decided to have them do that on the...

01:14:33.480 --> 01:14:49.480
We decided to have the arrest on the 31st where they could accomplish that rather than putting it so that it was February 1st, anniversary, February 1st, 1960 was the original date, 61 would have been the anniversary date.

01:14:49.480 --> 01:14:55.480
I mean, I'm not missing the point. The one day difference mattered because of a date you had to go register.

01:14:55.480 --> 01:15:07.480
The students had to register at the college so that they could stand the possibility of not losing a whole semester.

01:15:07.480 --> 01:15:13.480
There's much I'm sure to say about the experience of being on road gang.

01:15:43.480 --> 01:15:50.480
I think that this could be something that we could really begin to explore.

01:15:50.480 --> 01:16:09.480
Well, I guess I just looking at what had happened previously and looking at what, where there was the possibility of expanding it to something as we knew more about the potential use of nonviolence,

01:16:09.480 --> 01:16:17.480
I think that that's what would have led to the... let's try this Jalen strategy again, kind of thing.

01:16:17.480 --> 01:16:24.480
I would have made the point about the Jalen and this particular one being pivotal.

01:16:24.480 --> 01:16:37.480
I remember going to the NAACP National Convention in 1960 and there was a lady there named Claire Looper from Oklahoma City.

01:16:37.480 --> 01:16:51.480
She spent all of her time talking about sit-ins that had been done by the NAACP Youth Chapter in Tulsa, Oklahoma City, in Oklahoma City.

01:16:51.480 --> 01:16:59.480
I remember going away from that saying yes, but no one knew about them other than Claire Looper and a couple of other people.

01:16:59.480 --> 01:17:11.480
So that's again that thing that in history sometimes it's when you do something, when you have a context that accords significance rather than whether you've done it or not.

01:17:11.480 --> 01:17:18.480
I don't doubt that Claire Looper and her group had done sit-ins because she kept saying well the North Carolina people are...

01:17:18.480 --> 01:17:26.480
We know about the North Carolina people, they had an impact, we know about the friendship, I think they had an impact.

01:17:26.480 --> 01:17:35.480
And historically that's what we look for as we look at the social string that pushes this string, that pushes that one, that pushes that one.

01:17:35.480 --> 01:17:42.480
Well that's the key point I think I see the way you do that because you're able to set in motion very quickly.

01:17:42.480 --> 01:17:51.480
So the turning of attention, the rock hill and many things happen and you describe it because you're on the Jengaang but you know that many of these things...

01:17:51.480 --> 01:18:11.480
But you know that one of the things about being on the Jengaang is that we were coping with the situation of adjusting and being able to fit in and to do what we had to do to survive and to provide a witness on the Jengaang.

01:18:11.480 --> 01:18:18.480
What we didn't realize and couldn't possibly realize was the impact that was going on out there.

01:18:18.480 --> 01:18:34.480
On Sundays when there were a thousand people coming to see us, the only people that we could see would be a line of perhaps a hundred people that were coming straight into the dormitories where we were housed.

01:18:34.480 --> 01:18:52.480
We couldn't see all of those other people and we did not have communications network that enable us to know that so that one of the things that has been tremendously gratifying to me is to read what was going on on the outside.

01:18:52.480 --> 01:18:54.480
So you didn't have that information flow?

01:18:54.480 --> 01:18:58.480
Oh no, we did not have an information flow that told us.

01:18:58.480 --> 01:19:00.480
What have gone through those prison visits?

01:19:00.480 --> 01:19:01.480
But no.

01:19:01.480 --> 01:19:19.480
No. I mean if somebody told you, I don't recall anybody saying I'm just one of about a thousand people who are out here and it was deliberate on the part of the authorities to limit the number of people that we saw.

01:19:19.480 --> 01:19:36.480
So as to not break us but certainly not to encourage us, because one of the times we wound up in solitary confinement was because they wanted us to erect a fence to sort of corral the people who were coming to see us.

01:19:36.480 --> 01:19:43.480
And so if you're looking only on a straight line, I see 25 people. I don't know how many people along the ladderals there.

01:19:43.480 --> 01:19:49.480
So we have to stop for a second.

01:19:49.480 --> 01:19:53.480
You want to stop for a while? That's fine with me.

01:19:53.480 --> 01:19:57.480
I'm okay. You want some...

01:19:57.480 --> 01:20:00.480
Okay, we're back after short break.

01:20:00.480 --> 01:20:07.480
Okay, let me ask again, I have to hold back just a bit on it.

01:20:07.480 --> 01:20:22.480
In December, probably I'm guessing just after the training at Clapplin was I think the night through the 11th of December 1960, very close on those days.

01:20:22.480 --> 01:20:25.480
And then you're on a bus with Gordon Herod.

01:20:25.480 --> 01:20:26.480
Yes.

01:20:26.480 --> 01:20:33.480
Or you and he do some thinking and planning that will have just a very tremendous impact.

01:20:33.480 --> 01:20:37.480
So take me back to that ride and it's purpose and what you talked about.

01:20:37.480 --> 01:20:44.480
Okay, we were going from South Carolina after a training session back to New York.

01:20:44.480 --> 01:20:51.480
I think Gordon had a copy of Louis Fisher's book about Gandhi.

01:20:51.480 --> 01:20:58.480
And we may have even talked about Gandhi's famous march to the sea sort of thing.

01:20:58.480 --> 01:21:04.480
And I came up with the idea, it broke the idea of a Freedom Ride.

01:21:04.480 --> 01:21:19.480
And the Freedom Riders would essentially copy some of the basic pattern of a 1947 journey that had been staged by the Fellowship of Reconciliation and Corps jointly.

01:21:19.480 --> 01:21:24.480
That's the ride that George Houser was the scout on.

01:21:24.480 --> 01:21:31.480
So at some point in the journey, just chitchatting about one thing or another, the idea of a Freedom Ride comes up.

01:21:31.480 --> 01:21:33.480
So what were we going to call this thing?

01:21:33.480 --> 01:21:37.480
And I don't really know whether Gordon said Freedom Ride or I said Freedom Ride.

01:21:37.480 --> 01:21:43.480
It's not critical to me in terms of who said what at a time.

01:21:43.480 --> 01:21:55.480
But we went on to suggest that, well, how are we going to do with this thing in terms of the mechanics of the project?

01:21:55.480 --> 01:22:01.480
Well, so we're going to have to have people who are very well trained in nonviolence.

01:22:01.480 --> 01:22:20.480
And we're going to have to have somebody who will go down the route of the ride to send back very specific information about the town, the community, the bus schedules, the layout of the bus stations, the mass meetings, and all of that sort of thing.

01:22:20.480 --> 01:22:32.480
And so eventually I would become the person who would assume that particular function so that I could say that I was the scout for the Freedom Ride.

01:22:32.480 --> 01:22:49.480
And the choice of places was determined by the location of historically black colleges and universities going southward, that we had relationships with where we could house the riders.

01:22:49.480 --> 01:22:54.480
And also where we could have meetings to inform the local community.

01:22:54.480 --> 01:23:14.480
Because we didn't want to just take us trip through a community without making some connections with the local people who would follow up to make sure that whatever happened with us would be a springboard for them continuing to protest or taking advantage of any kinds of changes that would have occurred.

01:23:14.480 --> 01:23:22.480
This was just there to describe some of the close particulars but going back one level, this is audacious.

01:23:22.480 --> 01:23:28.480
This is how you're going to think you're going to be on this notion of pushing all the way through the deep south.

01:23:28.480 --> 01:23:38.480
Through the deep south, the original ride had not gone into the deep south because of the danger, element.

01:23:38.480 --> 01:23:46.480
But we were going to go through Mississippi, what we're going through Alabama, Mississippi, and end up in Louisiana.

01:23:46.480 --> 01:23:52.480
And we knew that the resistance there would be considerable.

01:23:52.480 --> 01:24:02.480
In fact, I think my suggestion was that if we get through the state of Alabama, we're going to have to have federal protection.

01:24:02.480 --> 01:24:09.480
Because Alabama was along with Mississippi the most resistant places that I thought we would encounter.

01:24:09.480 --> 01:24:15.480
And remember the NAACP had been outlawed in Alabama.

01:24:15.480 --> 01:24:25.480
So that's how you got the Southern Christian Leadership Conference in Dr. King's organization, a group going in, because it was illegal to be a member of the NAACP.

01:24:25.480 --> 01:24:29.480
So those three states we realized were going to be toughies.

01:24:29.480 --> 01:24:37.480
Now we also realized that there were places in South Carolina like Rock Hill, where the possibility was imminent.

01:24:37.480 --> 01:24:46.480
And of course in any of the small towns, in any one of those states, you could encounter all kinds of difficulties. You could lose your life.

01:24:46.480 --> 01:24:57.480
Tell me about the, so you and Carey [Gordon Carey] communicate this idea to the folks at the CORE National Office when you were alive?

01:24:57.480 --> 01:25:04.480
This is about the time that James Farmer became the executive secretary of course.

01:25:04.480 --> 01:25:09.480
That's exactly right. And for giving you the only thing to say, one more thing to contextualize the setup.

01:25:09.480 --> 01:25:17.480
You're right. This is right. In the late 1960s, early 1960s, when Jimmy Robinson's tenure is in question, certain tea, he's after all white, not black.

01:25:17.480 --> 01:25:19.480
That's right.

01:25:19.480 --> 01:25:34.480
Yeah. And so Jim Farmer was looking for a project. And this is one that had the potential to be very successful.

01:25:34.480 --> 01:25:48.480
And I don't think that we estimated how big it would become, because I think it ultimately was one of the signature protests of the entire Civil Rights Movement.

01:25:48.480 --> 01:26:05.480
And it involved all kinds of people. There were all kinds of inputs and all kinds of positive things that were brought together to address an issue that got national attention.

01:26:05.480 --> 01:26:22.480
And I don't think that we had that in mind. And evidence to the fact that we didn't have it in mind is that we had just a dozen or so very well trained, non-violent soldiers who were going to do this thing.

01:26:22.480 --> 01:26:33.480
And you know, you're not going to get a dozen people no matter how well trained they are through Alabama, Mississippi, and Louisiana.

01:26:33.480 --> 01:26:41.480
So I don't think that we had estimated the potential. And I think it's difficult to do that anyway.

01:26:41.480 --> 01:26:47.480
Did you think about the King, my joint? Is that something you want?

01:26:47.480 --> 01:27:09.480
It was not something that I was anticipating. And it's something that given the magnitude of Dr. King's contributions, I do not hold one reserve in terms of my respect for Dr. King that he didn't become a freedom rider.

01:27:09.480 --> 01:27:26.480
He was on the advisory board, National Advisory Board for Corps. He had been perhaps the primary influence in flushing out non-violence as a strategy for promoting social change.

01:27:26.480 --> 01:27:32.480
And to me, that was, that's enough of a contribution. I don't care that he did not become a freedom rider.

01:27:32.480 --> 01:27:37.480
Maybe the question is too obvious, but I don't know the answer. Why wouldn't you agree to that?

01:27:37.480 --> 01:27:40.480
Why wasn't I afraid of that? Okay.

01:27:40.480 --> 01:27:43.480
But you did all the scouting. I did all the scouting.

01:27:43.480 --> 01:28:00.480
And then after setting the whole thing up, I drew the assignment of being the person in Jackson who would take care of all of the writers when they were released.

01:28:00.480 --> 01:28:18.480
Not an assignment before that, though. My assignment right after the bus was burned in Anniston was in Montgomery, Alabama. And in Montgomery, I lived in the home of Ralph Abernathy.

01:28:18.480 --> 01:28:25.480
This is when, after the event in the church, Montgomery was under martial law.

01:28:25.480 --> 01:28:30.480
The church was thousands of whites. I didn't agree whites from mass and outside the rally at Reverend Ralph Abernathy's church.

01:28:30.480 --> 01:28:43.480
Yeah, okay. So, Town's under martial law and freedom rider start to trickle in. I was training writers there.

01:28:43.480 --> 01:28:51.480
I'd have to go to the trailways or the Greyhound Station to pick up writers.

01:28:51.480 --> 01:28:59.480
We would know how many writers were coming in, but we would know their names, but we didn't match names with people.

01:28:59.480 --> 01:29:16.480
So the question was, you know, how are you going to get down there? Well, first of all, right outside of Ralph Abernathy's house, about a half a block up, there was a Jeep with a National Gargement driving and another National Gargement in the back seat with a rifle across.

01:29:16.480 --> 01:29:28.480
So these guys would give us an escort to within a block of the bus station. Trailways are Greyhound. They disappear.

01:29:28.480 --> 01:29:42.480
We got to get with a local guy who was my driver. We got to get from there, pass all of the red necks to pick up the writers.

01:29:42.480 --> 01:29:55.480
We know they're five, but we don't know them. So this is what I would do. I would stand in an area near a telephone booth. I would know the gender of the people.

01:29:55.480 --> 01:30:05.480
As soon as I saw the dial Ralph Abernathy's number, I would go over and wrap on. Come on, come on. And that worked for a number of times.

01:30:05.480 --> 01:30:18.480
And we'd go back with those people, pass them off, incidentally. We'd go back past them off. We would get in our vehicle. The Jeep would intercept us again. Take us back to Avenathy's house.

01:30:18.480 --> 01:30:30.480
Now this was the projection that we are getting. When we needed the National Guard, it wasn't there. We were on our own. When we got back to a safe neighborhood, Ralph Abernathy lived on a black neighborhood.

01:30:30.480 --> 01:30:41.480
There was not a lot of chance that there was going to be somebody who was going to come in and do us harm there. And it's from there that I was assigned to Jackson.

01:30:41.480 --> 01:30:53.480
Yeah. Thinking back as best you can to watch this whole ride unfold, maybe especially from Rock Hill forward.

01:30:53.480 --> 01:31:10.480
I mean, really watching your vision unfold in the spectacularly fashion that it did in all of it, tumble in violence and care of the federal government's momentum.

01:31:10.480 --> 01:31:18.480
I mean, you're not a very young man. You're in your early 20s. That's right. Yeah.

01:31:18.480 --> 01:31:44.480
I'm interested in your response and your sense of what's happening. It was a sense of gratification. It was also a sense of responsibility for people who would be injured, who might carry those injuries the rest of their lives.

01:31:44.480 --> 01:32:03.480
It's one thing to ask me to do that as a person. It's another thing. But I also thought that we were in this together. And what happened to any one of us could have happened to any others of us.

01:32:03.480 --> 01:32:14.480
And I would have been willing to do. And I was gratified that there were brothers and sisters, white, black, who were similarly minded.

01:32:14.480 --> 01:32:30.480
So I think we had grown up to the point here of the level of sacrifice that might be expected. Always hoping that that would not be the case, but realizing that it certainly could be the case.

01:32:30.480 --> 01:32:39.480
Obviously, the experience of violence by that point was not entirely new to the movement, but it was pretty parotious.

01:32:39.480 --> 01:32:47.480
Yes. And I wonder about your reaction to that. Did that change any part of your perspective?

01:32:47.480 --> 01:33:07.480
No, because I think that the idea was that we can't let violence intimidate us into doing any less than what we think we should be doing. And that would be insisting that we be treated just like any other citizens.

01:33:07.480 --> 01:33:14.480
How about perspective of federal government and Kennedy administration, particularly after what happened?

01:33:14.480 --> 01:33:34.480
Well, the federal government was not our ally. I think that they were sort of annoyed that there were all these critical international issues. And then you got this bunch of blacks and whites who want to ride through the South challenging the culture of segregation.

01:33:34.480 --> 01:33:55.480
I'd be particularly critical of the FBI because there was no community that I worked in where I could talk to an FBI agent. I did once think on a sort of intuitive court that there was an FBI guy that I could say something to.

01:33:55.480 --> 01:34:09.480
And this was when I was working in Jackson about two months later I wound up in federal court. The agent had hope that he could implicate me in a conspiracy.

01:34:09.480 --> 01:34:30.480
Well, it turns out I had been tactful enough that when I testified it really didn't help their case. So the Justice Department presence with people like John Doar was often welcomed and was sincere.

01:34:30.480 --> 01:34:35.480
That's one of the reasons.

01:34:35.480 --> 01:34:41.480
Let me have you recount that last point one more time.

01:34:41.480 --> 01:34:56.480
Well, I think the Justice Department, the Justice Department and John Doar. John Doar did a lot of very good work I think in Mississippi and voter registration protections and so forth.

01:34:56.480 --> 01:35:08.480
But the sincere involvement and the by the federal bureaucracy in protecting rights and so forth was grossly negligent.

01:35:08.480 --> 01:35:23.480
I think to the Kennedys this was all about politics. It wasn't about a moral commitment to protect citizens who were being disenfranchised by the local political culture.

01:35:23.480 --> 01:35:41.480
I'm asking some of these things because later in our conversation I'll ask you some kind of reflective things and these are part of the ground. I think you go across in the strain.

01:35:41.480 --> 01:35:55.480
It must have been a year or so. We'll get on about this later in the course of this and it must have been very interesting to watch everything turned towards Jackson towards Parchman [Farm.

01:35:55.480 --> 01:35:58.480
And it became really a national.

01:35:58.480 --> 01:36:00.480
It did. Yes, it did.

01:36:00.480 --> 01:36:17.480
We had people coming in from various parts of the country. We had various religious groups. I remember the Episcopalians, the Church of Latter-day Saints groups.

01:36:17.480 --> 01:36:34.480
It was a good cross section of America. That's the situation where the Freedom Rides started out as a specific protest involving a very small group.

01:36:34.480 --> 01:36:41.480
They wound up being a national movement essentially. I don't think we could have predicted that.

01:36:41.480 --> 01:36:56.480
What was your broad sense of the prospects of the movement say is that summer of 61 wound down. This is where our community is looking for the best choices about how to move forward.

01:36:56.480 --> 01:37:02.480
What was your sense of what the Freedom Rides at that point meant and what opportunities seemed ahead of you?

01:37:02.480 --> 01:37:16.480
I saw a non-violent direct action as being a possible route to promoting some of the kinds of changes that we wanted to promote.

01:37:16.480 --> 01:37:33.480
At the same time, I was aware of the impatience of people who had been tactically non-violent, who were starting to listen to what is a dominant cultural theme, which is violence.

01:37:33.480 --> 01:37:48.480
There was a kind of innocence, a moral focus to the early part of the movement. To be a non-violent movement, if you go back to Gandhi, requires a lot of discipline, a lot of training.

01:37:48.480 --> 01:37:58.480
I think that the fact that we were able to do that is to ask people in a society that is predominantly violent through its core, to continue to maintain that.

01:37:58.480 --> 01:38:17.480
I think that that is the sad thing about what happened with the deaths of Dr. King. I mean, I think that Dr. King's star by the time he was assassinated had really started to wane because the violent elements were so ever present.

01:38:17.480 --> 01:38:26.480
Until they were becoming considerable in terms of how we go about promoting the chains that we want to promote.

01:38:26.480 --> 01:38:34.480
You would move from the Freedom Rides into the Kofo experience.

01:38:34.480 --> 01:38:43.480
Yes, now I didn't do a lot with the Kofo experience. I was there when Kofo was founded.

01:38:43.480 --> 01:39:00.480
It seemed to be a natural kind of thing. To the segregationless and the culture of segregation in Mississippi, there would be no difference between core NAACP, SNCC, SCLC.

01:39:00.480 --> 01:39:10.480
To the segregation, those were all the same. We had different strengths in terms of what organizations could contribute to the struggle.

01:39:10.480 --> 01:39:22.480
So I have always described to the notion that there were some people who would be active in the NAACP, who would never be active in core, who would never be active in SCLC.

01:39:22.480 --> 01:39:35.480
But we need their push as a thrust for this movement forward. And so I don't go back and belabor any negative points about the organizations that were involved.

01:39:35.480 --> 01:39:47.480
Because I think there were enough niches for all of us to put our shoulders to the plow to move this wretched animal of segregation out of the way.

01:39:47.480 --> 01:39:51.480
What about Bob Moses? Do you work with that?

01:39:51.480 --> 01:40:16.480
Bob Moses, a brilliant guy, a visionary. When we were focused on taking care of Freedom Riders in Jackson, which is when I first met Bob Moses, Bob Moses was involved in managing the campaigns of some of the local ministry.

01:40:16.480 --> 01:40:36.480
The local ministers who were running for Congress. He was looking ahead to the potential for political status, solidifying some of the gains that we were trying to get to happen or to occur.

01:40:36.480 --> 01:41:00.480
His book is on that the The Algebra Project. He and Dave Dennis worked together. I have high respect for Bob Moses. One of the things I respect about Bob Moses is that there were people involved in this movement, who in my opinion were quite a bit centered around themselves and their significance.

01:41:00.480 --> 01:41:12.480
I think Bob Moses saw the larger picture. And I think his very low key manner is to push the issues and the important things as opposed to pushing the individual.

01:41:12.480 --> 01:41:28.480
In 62, I guess you reached a point where because of reasons related to your deferment status, you will certain choices are very stark in front of you. Can you talk about what they were and how to...

01:41:28.480 --> 01:41:41.480
After college, I had received a number of deferments. I had gotten to the point of being classified. I think it was 1A.

01:41:41.480 --> 01:41:56.480
I received when I was still right in the midst of working in Jackson. I received a notice that I had to report to Fort Jackson, South Carolina for induction into the army.

01:41:56.480 --> 01:42:14.480
Now, I had been negligent to make the argument that I would object to military service on the basis of conscious. Because that philosophy of nonviolence had convinced me that I would not be a very good soldier.

01:42:14.480 --> 01:42:27.480
But I would be willing to serve my country in an alternate capacity. So not being a CEO, I get to Fort Jackson, South Carolina. We take all of these preliminary tests the first day.

01:42:27.480 --> 01:42:39.480
The sergeant says, looks good. The next day, he says, well, I see you have an arrest record here. I said, indeed, I do.

01:42:39.480 --> 01:42:50.480
Well, you're not morally fit to serve in the military, except we'll think about this. And when he said that, he said, we're going to let you go for a few days.

01:42:50.480 --> 01:43:02.480
And I went very quickly to resurrect the interest that I had shown in a couple of graduate schools. One was at Atlanta University in Atlanta, Georgia.

01:43:02.480 --> 01:43:16.480
The other one that I had been admitted to was University of Washington, West Coast, and University of Illinois, Champaign, or Urbana. So I had those choices.

01:43:16.480 --> 01:43:30.480
But I checked to see when sessions were starting. And so the sessions were starting for some of school at Atlanta University. So I found myself in graduate school rather quickly.

01:43:30.480 --> 01:43:38.480
And that, of course, staved off the business of having to try to resurrect conscientious objective status.

01:43:38.480 --> 01:43:43.480
And you would spend the final summer of 16 degree, I think, in Mississippi, right?

01:43:43.480 --> 01:44:05.480
In Mississippi, one year of work on my master's degree, there's another interesting story to this, by the way. Right after the bus had been burned in Anniston, and I was doing some short assignments, I went to the University of Wisconsin at University of Wisconsin–Madison to work for Corps.

01:44:05.480 --> 01:44:10.480
And they were asking questions about the freedom rides, so forth, and so on.

01:44:10.480 --> 01:44:26.480
So you feel secretary assignment. And so I met a professor whose last name I think was Rice. And he said, you haven't taken the law school aptitude test. He said, but I'm going to recommend you to law school.

01:44:26.480 --> 01:44:39.480
Now, after Claflin and being involved in the movement, I had actually thought how I could get into a profession that would enable me to continue to contribute to the movement.

01:44:39.480 --> 01:44:53.480
And I decided that law would be that rather than biology. But one year after I had worked on my master's degree in biology, I went home to great falls, and I'm thumbing through this mail.

01:44:53.480 --> 01:45:05.480
I come across this letter admitting me to law school at University of Wisconsin. So he said, you admit it, you will have to take the law school aptitude test as a matter of record.

01:45:05.480 --> 01:45:18.480
So that's how I wound up going into biology or continuing to work to biology. And I was successful in biology.

01:45:18.480 --> 01:45:27.480
So I actually wound up getting a couple of graduate teaching assistantships. And I chose the one at the University of Iowa.

01:45:27.480 --> 01:45:37.480
Tell me about the end when I didn't go to law school. No, I didn't go to law school. I was already halfway through a master's degree in biology. And I'd always liked biology.

01:45:37.480 --> 01:45:47.480
So rather than changing to something that was entirely different, even though it was closer to the movement, I decided to keep going in biology.

01:45:47.480 --> 01:45:51.480
Well, as you mentioned, you were earlier met on a spinning and Matthew J. Perry Jr. You were a lawyer.

01:45:51.480 --> 01:46:00.480
Yeah. William Kunstler, Carl Rachlin, I met a variety of lawyers who were favorable influences.

01:46:00.480 --> 01:46:10.480
Tell me about them. Let me tell you about my, my, my, my couple of lawyers that are not very well known.

01:46:10.480 --> 01:46:23.480
When the writers were freedom rider, were being tried in Jackson, Mississippi, there were perhaps five or six lawyers in Jackson, Mississippi, black lawyers.

01:46:23.480 --> 01:46:35.480
There was Sydney Thorpe, was the only lawyer who had been trained, well, he'd been trained in a Big Ten Conference, I think.

01:46:35.480 --> 01:46:49.480
But he would not take freedom rider cases. There was Jack H. Young Sr, who started out as a postal clerk, and had taken law as a correspondence, who was our chief legal contact.

01:46:49.480 --> 01:47:00.480
There was R. Jess Brown, who used to be a social studies teacher at one of the high schools, who had graduated from Texas Southern.

01:47:00.480 --> 01:47:14.480
And there was another man named Carsie Hall, who was also a male clerk. And so those were our core lawyers, R. Jess Brown, Jack H. Young Sr, and Carsie Hall.

01:47:14.480 --> 01:47:26.480
And if it was a federal case, we would get people like Derrick Bell and Constance Baker Motley, William Kunstler, or Carl Rachlin.

01:47:26.480 --> 01:47:37.480
We would get, you know, some other reinforcements. But it was always a nucleus of local guys that sort of coordinated things. And tried most of the freedom rider cases.

01:47:38.480 --> 01:47:42.480
Tell me about the summer of 1963 going in Mississippi.

01:47:42.480 --> 01:47:45.480
The summer, you did a final three months?

01:47:45.480 --> 01:47:53.480
Oh, yes. The final three months. I worked with Aaron E. Henry in Clarksdale, Mississippi Mississippi.

01:47:54.480 --> 01:48:10.480
And Aaron E. Henry and the Clarksdale, Mississippi NAACP were involved in a selective buying program, actually a boycott, of downtown Clarksdale, Mississippi.

01:48:11.480 --> 01:48:32.480
So being there for just three months, I was just fitting into an augmenting and existing program having to do with issues of police brutality, issues of discriminating against black people in the downtown area, in the stores, so forth and so on.

01:48:32.480 --> 01:48:44.480
But the other thing I did there was to be the focus of a freedom school that was just a block of so away from Aaron E. Henry's drugstore.

01:48:44.480 --> 01:48:57.480
And we would have coming into the center, I'd say, 2025 young people every day. And we talked freedom songs, history of blacks in America, so forth, and so on.

01:48:57.480 --> 01:49:11.480
And it was there when the March on Washington was to take place. And so my choice was to stay in Clarksdale, Mississippi or to go to the March on Washington.

01:49:11.480 --> 01:49:23.480
And I opted to stay in Clarksdale, Mississippi. And I remember as I told you there, helping to put together the sign March on Washington for jobs in freedom.

01:49:23.480 --> 01:49:40.480
And then with SCLC, SNCC, core NAACP and COFO, which was the Council of Federated Organization, sort of pulling them all together on that sign, which the young people from Clark Dale took to the March on Washington.

01:49:40.480 --> 01:49:45.480
And you went back, I guess, to Atlanta for a second year at a Lanyard University?

01:49:45.480 --> 01:49:49.480
And then to the University of Iowa for the PhD.

01:49:49.480 --> 01:49:52.480
Let me close it and pause here and take a break.

01:49:52.480 --> 01:49:57.480
We really put you to hard work.

01:49:57.480 --> 01:50:03.480
We are back after a break for some refreshment. Thank you for that.

01:50:03.480 --> 01:50:06.480
Thank you for that.

01:50:06.480 --> 01:50:11.480
I'd like to ask, just a few things. Let me start just for the tape record.

01:50:11.480 --> 01:50:18.480
John, that would be good if we can you just say recap in a simple descriptive way.

01:50:18.480 --> 01:50:23.480
The number of organizations inside COFO and say once more what that was.

01:50:23.480 --> 01:50:29.480
Okay, COFO was the Council of Federated Organizations.

01:50:29.480 --> 01:50:50.480
And the representative organizations were SNCC, the Student Non-Violate Coordinating Committee, the SCLC, the Southern Christian Leadership Conference, the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the NAACP, and core the Congress of Racial Equality.

01:50:50.480 --> 01:50:53.480
We both together constitute COFO.

01:50:53.480 --> 01:51:00.480
And you had earlier talked about how from the perspective of the average white Mississippi segregationists they would have all been one broad men.

01:51:00.480 --> 01:51:04.480
All one side-added people. That's right. That is true.

01:51:04.480 --> 01:51:10.480
Let me have you on. Very interested in, we can't do justice because we'll just hear a time for a summary.

01:51:10.480 --> 01:51:19.480
But talk about first year experiencing graduate school, particularly in Iowa, and then move to the broader question of your work as something.

01:51:19.480 --> 01:51:25.480
Last year, Iowa, I was of course the only African American student in the department.

01:51:25.480 --> 01:51:32.480
There were a couple of Asian Indian students in the department.

01:51:32.480 --> 01:51:42.480
Did well academically was assigned to be a graduate teaching assistant in a very large course.

01:51:42.480 --> 01:51:48.480
We had a lot of life science. It was actually an introductory level biology course.

01:51:48.480 --> 01:51:54.480
And we had two responsibilities for the sections that we were assigned.

01:51:54.480 --> 01:51:59.480
We had the students for a laboratory for a couple of hours a week.

01:51:59.480 --> 01:52:03.480
And we had them for an hour or so in a discussion group.

01:52:03.480 --> 01:52:13.480
The discussion group, we could deal with points of information that students had questions about based on the lecture.

01:52:13.480 --> 01:52:27.480
Because of the very large number of people in the class, the lecturers were just given the time to present the information to embellish or to clarify something that was up to the TA.

01:52:27.480 --> 01:52:38.480
As the only African American student, there had been previously an African American student from Louisiana who had graduated.

01:52:38.480 --> 01:52:47.480
And indeed my mentor, one of the persons that was influential in sending me to Iowa, actually compared me to his previous student that had been there.

01:52:47.480 --> 01:52:53.480
And that was sort of an automatic niche for me to be in.

01:52:53.480 --> 01:53:01.480
There were of course the usual cross section of people, some of whom became close friends until today.

01:53:01.480 --> 01:53:05.480
But there were also the people who just sort of tolerated you because you were there.

01:53:05.480 --> 01:53:10.480
And to them, they would have been just as happy if you weren't there.

01:53:10.480 --> 01:53:18.480
But the professors were across the spectrum too. Some very conservative ones were particularly standoffish.

01:53:18.480 --> 01:53:30.480
But I found enough favor in professors and they respected me enough as a student until I didn't have any major problems with graduate work at Iowa.

01:53:30.480 --> 01:53:47.480
I had decided to go to Iowa because I felt that if not a neutral place to go, it might be at least a place where I could find some direction to do something that was not good.

01:53:47.480 --> 01:53:52.480
I could do something that was a potential passion for me.

01:53:52.480 --> 01:53:59.480
The leader in the field at the time had left Iowa and gone to Austin, Texas.

01:53:59.480 --> 01:54:12.480
And even though Austin, Texas has a reputation of being a bit more enlightened than some other cities in Texas, I didn't come out of a movement where I was fighting discrimination in its most bladed form day in and day out.

01:54:12.480 --> 01:54:20.480
I wanted to take that same mantle to do graduate work at Texas even though the pre-immunite scholar in the field was at Texas.

01:54:20.480 --> 01:54:24.480
So that was sort of one of the things that compelled me to go to Iowa.

01:54:24.480 --> 01:54:31.480
Now I had mentioned that I could have gone to Washington, Seattle, or Champaign, or a Banner.

01:54:31.480 --> 01:54:38.480
Champaign, or a Banner, actually did not have the fit program that I was primarily interested in.

01:54:38.480 --> 01:54:44.480
And I wasn't quite sure I wanted to go way out on the west coast, so I wound up going to Iowa.

01:54:44.480 --> 01:54:52.480
Tell me about the things that have been most important to you as a scholar and researcher over the years.

01:54:52.480 --> 01:55:02.480
Okay, as a researcher, eventually I got into an area of biology that's called electron microscopy.

01:55:02.480 --> 01:55:12.480
And my specific interest in electron microscopy was to start with the very small structures that are inside of a living system.

01:55:12.480 --> 01:55:24.480
And to see what happens when some of those structures transform into entities that are important for the reproduction of the organism.

01:55:24.480 --> 01:55:31.480
So there was something that's called a electron microscopy, or from Latin capillus, meaning a thread.

01:55:31.480 --> 01:55:34.480
I actually studied how these threads came to be.

01:55:34.480 --> 01:55:47.480
And in the mature reproductive structure of the organisms that I studied, the threads have a function because they prevent the organism from putting all of its reproductive structures out at once.

01:55:47.480 --> 01:55:58.480
So they are out over a longer time period, increasing the possibility that some of those reproductive structures will then propagate the organism.

01:55:58.480 --> 01:56:13.480
The other interest that I had was using the electron microscope to answer certain questions that you couldn't answer given the limitations of a regular microscope.

01:56:13.480 --> 01:56:18.480
So you can see things with a regular microscope that are only so close to each other.

01:56:18.480 --> 01:56:23.480
With an electron microscope, you can see them much closer. That's something we call resolution.

01:56:23.480 --> 01:56:36.480
So with improved resolution, a question that might be subjective with a light microscope suddenly becomes objective with an electron microscope because you can see more clearly what is there.

01:56:36.480 --> 01:56:55.480
So that was my interest in using the electron microscope to answer those kinds of questions which were then involved in defining how one species of organism was different from another species that was close to related.

01:56:55.480 --> 01:57:03.480
So it was a speciation using electron microscopy to resolve the questions.

01:57:04.480 --> 01:57:19.480
Let me turn, I forget because I know that it's just the barest summary, but for our work today, I want to turn back to surprise and then the struggle.

01:57:20.480 --> 01:57:31.480
And maybe to a few retrospective kinds of questions. I know that in, which is past 50 members, obviously, of the Green Line, the Green Line.

01:57:31.480 --> 01:57:37.480
There are many different ways that people approach that memory.

01:57:37.480 --> 01:57:48.480
So I'm interested in the question of different interpretations of the ride and impact and how you see the significance of the Green Line from this distance.

01:57:48.480 --> 01:58:02.480
Well, I see them as being one of the most important, the most inclusive, the most integrative protest as a part of the total civil rights structure.

01:58:02.480 --> 01:58:09.480
We were talking about attribution of who did this and who did that.

01:58:10.480 --> 01:58:20.480
There is no question that the rides were conceived by and executed primarily by the Congress of Racial Equality.

01:58:20.480 --> 01:58:35.480
After the bus was burned in Anniston, when the riders were no longer capable of continuing, we received a very nice contribution from the students Nashville and the Nashville movement.

01:58:35.480 --> 01:58:48.480
Now, that contribution is to be given a great deal of credit, but its credit should not extend to the suggestion that the corps was incapable of continuing.

01:58:48.480 --> 01:58:58.480
In any kind of movement, there are strategic times that you move, and obviously you can't move if you physically incapable at that moment.

01:58:59.480 --> 01:59:07.480
That does not mean that you're not in charge of the sequence of events that is part of an ongoing process.

01:59:07.480 --> 01:59:24.480
So my disappointment was those who would rewrite the history as if the Congress of Racial Equality, the people who originated and for the most part sponsored the rides, that these were sort of like rookies who didn't know what they were doing.

01:59:24.480 --> 01:59:46.480
We appreciate the contribution of the Nashville people, but it was simply a contribution that was a part of an ongoing process, not a contribution that should consume the origin of the process and the propagation of the events that we label with the term freedom ride.

01:59:46.480 --> 01:59:58.480
Did you, after you departed for Iowa and then had your, so long on of your career, was it an academic year in Pennsylvania? Did you have a river dam in the South?

01:59:58.480 --> 02:00:15.480
No, with the exception of going back for visits. No question the South has changed tremendously, but the fundamental infrastructure of racism and segregation that call the shots in the South.

02:00:15.480 --> 02:00:35.480
In the South, in 1960, are still in place. They have slightly different labels. They accomplish their goals by slightly different means, but there has been no real fundamental shift in who really calls the signals.

02:00:35.480 --> 02:00:50.480
We can have black public officials, but sometimes the strength of what those people can do is actually called by shots from the same people who were calling the shots 50 years ago.

02:00:50.480 --> 02:01:10.480
So there has been change, a lot of its surface change, and there's still an awful lot of work to do. And in this recent thing of a society that is colorblind, much of the legal weight for making some meaningful changes is continually eroded.

02:01:10.480 --> 02:01:23.480
And if you're talking about making changes in the Southern context, ultimately that has to come down to the administrators of federal programs and so forth.

02:01:23.480 --> 02:01:43.480
And very often these are very obviously discriminatory witness Katrina witness GI veil availability and so forth. We go back to the 60s and we still have to push the bad guy out of the way yet.

02:01:43.480 --> 02:02:05.480
From the near distance in terms of time when you were saying in Iowa and beginning your work as an academic, did you ever have occasion to, I'm sure the question came to your mind, the general occasion to doubt the non violence as a tactical means.

02:02:05.480 --> 02:02:10.480
Did you ever think that it won't work here in the American context or?

02:02:10.480 --> 02:02:27.480
No, I've always had faith that it would work. I think there is a residual moral conscious in a significant number of Americans that makes it possible for nonviolent tactics to work.

02:02:27.480 --> 02:02:41.480
They must, however, be waged within a context of people who are well trained and who can articulate what it is that they are doing and why are they doing it.

02:02:41.480 --> 02:02:49.480
One is heartened by some of the nonviolent type things that have occurred in the Middle East.

02:02:49.480 --> 02:03:05.480
So I think that there, you know, there's still the possibility for nonviolent direct action being a positive social positive, the promoting change process.

02:03:05.480 --> 02:03:19.480
In having to hold the view for all of the many reasons that supported, that things have not changed so much, does it?

02:03:19.480 --> 02:03:28.480
Does it have the effect of, well, what have been the implications for your sense of the American project over the longer term?

02:03:28.480 --> 02:03:36.480
Do you think this is a place that might find its way one day to a more just social order?

02:03:36.480 --> 02:03:55.480
I hope so. And if one looks at, for example, the recent election of Barack Obama, I think what we had happening there, and by the way, I was immensely surprised that Barack Obama was elected.

02:03:55.480 --> 02:04:03.480
Because my mind was clicking back to what I know the situation to have been in the 50s, 60s and 70s.

02:04:03.480 --> 02:04:09.480
It was a young people who went out and rallied for the first time for a change.

02:04:09.480 --> 02:04:18.480
The unfortunate thing is that many of those young people have not persisted with insisting that the change was there.

02:04:18.480 --> 02:04:32.480
So what we see now in the inability of Barack Obama to govern is the kinds of factors that if they had been dominant, would not have permitted him to be elected in the first place.

02:04:32.480 --> 02:04:43.480
Because everything he decides to do, the idea is to obstruct him and to prevent positive change from occurring a taking place.

02:04:43.480 --> 02:04:58.480
If the young people were just as involved in making sure that we are sending to people to Congress who are going to cooperate and who are going to be collegial and who are going to be bipartisan, that be hope.

02:04:58.480 --> 02:05:03.480
And I have to think that the young people hold that hope.

02:05:03.480 --> 02:05:18.480
Looking back, the movement was your passion and your work, and you struggled in very difficult contexts for years there at the opening of the decade of the 60s.

02:05:18.480 --> 02:05:33.480
Are there ways in which, as you think about that, are there costs that were born by you in an ongoing fashion? Is there a legacy of cost or complication in any way for you?

02:05:34.480 --> 02:05:54.480
Well, this isn't an interesting question because when I think back to the time, the energy and the passion that I put into a movement to be accepted as a citizen, as a human being,

02:05:54.480 --> 02:06:11.480
there are times when I wonder, what could I have done with that time to do something else that is automatically forthcoming if you happen to be born in this country and your skin happens to be white instead of brown?

02:06:11.480 --> 02:06:13.480
That gals me on occasion.

02:06:13.480 --> 02:06:27.480
Because I think we have lost as a nation a lot of potential, and we still lose that potential when all you have to do is to be born white, you have all these privileges, but if you're black, you're going to have to fight for them.

02:06:27.480 --> 02:06:39.480
We need all of us on the same page playing the same tune in order to be competitive internationally at this point.

02:06:39.480 --> 02:06:49.480
What if I ask one final question and by any further comments you might want to make, what would great falls on South Carolina look like if you went back to that?

02:06:49.480 --> 02:06:53.480
Oh, great falls, South Carolina.

02:06:53.480 --> 02:07:04.480
A fundamental disconnect with the mainstream of American society in terms of almost every aspect of life.

02:07:05.480 --> 02:07:19.480
When I drive through great falls, I see a number of men, my age, sitting out under a tree just biting the time away.

02:07:19.480 --> 02:07:31.480
But for the grace of God, there go I sitting there. These are people without hope for whom the current century has passed.

02:07:31.480 --> 02:07:37.480
And quite honestly, I don't know what will happen to them.

02:07:37.480 --> 02:07:47.480
But the tragedy is that they have been lost, but the tragedy that is even worse is that their children in many instances have been lost too.

02:07:47.480 --> 02:08:00.480
And that's downright depressing. I can't think of any reason why an industry would go to great falls. You don't have a well-trained labor force.

02:08:00.480 --> 02:08:12.480
You don't have the kinds of amenities that are necessary to run a business ethically for profit, so forth, and so on.

02:08:12.480 --> 02:08:21.480
I really don't know. It's one of those questions my parents would say, I'll leave it to God because I don't really have a solution for great falls.

02:08:21.480 --> 02:08:33.480
Except to say that it hurts me that there is not hope for a future that is bright for great falls.

02:08:33.480 --> 02:08:40.480
And what I'm saying might be interpreted to be from a black perspective. I'm a black man.

02:08:40.480 --> 02:08:51.480
But the South in its effort to keep black people down is also cheated white people, especially poor white people, because they're in the same boat.

02:08:51.480 --> 02:09:03.480
The white people should get together with the black people and move the monkey off the bat. But many of them are holding onto the fact, well, at least I'm white.

02:09:03.480 --> 02:09:16.480
Are there things we haven't talked about? I would mention one other thing.

02:09:16.480 --> 02:09:40.480
I think that scholars are frequently misunderstood. And I think they are especially misunderstood in the African-American community, because we've had so few models on which to generate an idea as to their importance or to their significance.

02:09:40.480 --> 02:09:53.480
But when I tell people I have a PhD in botany, they could identify if I have a PhD in agriculture or something that they have a life experience that they can connect to it.

02:09:53.480 --> 02:10:08.480
But to them, my whole contribution to the total of my being and the being of my nation, my country and my race is not comprehensible at all.

02:10:08.480 --> 02:10:20.480
And a couple of that with the fact that even my parents, I couldn't explain to them exactly what it is that's my passion. I do.

02:10:20.480 --> 02:10:42.480
But in the majority society, usually there is at least some way of making a connection that rings clear. But that's a sort of lonely feeling being out there. But I see my contribution as being more than to black people, but being to the nation as a whole.

02:10:42.480 --> 02:10:49.480
Thank you for welcoming us here to the prospect today. My pleasure, sir. It's been a real honor and privilege to go. Thank you.

02:10:49.480 --> 02:10:56.480
Thank you so much.

02:10:56.480 --> 02:11:06.480
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

